Red Wine Quality by Chelsey De Dios

We will be exploring data regarding qualities of nearly 1600 red wines. This dataset includes a variety of objective observations on red wine and a rating of the wines based on analysis by a group of wine experts. I chose this dataset as I used to be a server at a high end restaurant and I would be interested to know if the conventional knowledge that we were taught to help customers is true within this dataset.

Wine Quality

It looks like most of the wine with of middling quality according to our experts with most having a score of 5-6 out of 10. This makes me wonder about how this data was collected, and why so few were rated as exceptionally poor or excellent

Alcohol Content By Volume

Here we can see that the bulk of our alcohol content is between 9% and 11% by volume with a little bit of an outlier around ~14.75%

Residual Sugar

Our residual sugar is positively skewed with most of the data within 1.5-3 g / dm^3. There are some pretty far out numbers going up to around 15.5 g / dm^3. Seeing that most of the residual sugar is in the 1.5-3.5 g/dm^3 is a huge alarm for me. Sugar in wine varies greatly and can be anywhere from 0 to over 200 g/L (g/L is equivalent to g/dm^3) The fact that we only have wines under 20 g/L tells me we are dealing with only dry wines. There should be a relationship with sugar and alcohol content, as wines with more alcohol should have less sugar as sugar is eaten by yeast to make alcohol in wine.

Density

Our density has a nice, normal distribution with most wines falling between .995 and .999 g/cm^3. There should be a relationship between alcohol, sugar and density, as sugar rich wines should be thicker while alcohol rich wines should be thinner.

Sulphates

Our sulphates seem to have a fairly normal distribution save for a few outliers. sulphates are used to preserve wine, as our datas accompanying text file indicates it is an antimicrobial and an antioxidant which leads to sulfur dioxide or sulphites in wine.

Total and Free Sulfur Dioxide

The free sulfur dioxide has a positive skew as does our total sulfur dioxide. Wine makers may be trying to keep these numbers low as sulphites have an undeservedly bad reputation, a topic for another day.

Later on in our analysis I would be interested to see if our wine experts noticed any difference in our sulphate/sulphite rich wine and those that are less so. I expect that we will find that they didnt spot the difference. We should find that there is an relationship between sulphates/sulphites and alcohol content, as alcohol rich wines should not need as much preservative as those wines with less alcohol.

Fixed and Volatile Acidity

Our volatile acidity also seems to have a fairly normal distribution. It will be interesting to see the relationship between sugar, chloride, acidity, citric acid and quality later on.

Citric Acid

Here we see that our citric acid is pretty evenly distrbuted between 0 and .5. It is interesting that the distribution fell this neatly.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Our dataset has 1599 observations with 13 variables all numeric since we converted our integer of quality to numeric to make the data easier to work with

We have a lot of middling quality wines so it makes it more difficult to spot what it was that necessarily put the higher quality wines at that rating. If our data had more very low and very high quality wines vs just a bunch of average wines we might be able to draw more meaningful conclusions than I believe we will find here today.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

  • I am interested in what factors put some wines at a higher quality rating than others, particularly if sulphates/sulphites made much of a difference to our experts.

  • I am interested in the relationship of alcohol content to preservatives, including acids and sulphates/sulphites.

  • There should be a relationship between alcohol and sugar content and density.

  • I would like to explore the relationship between volatile acidity and citric acid as I would expect that there volatile acidity would go up with the addition of citric acid.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I did change wine quality from an integers to a numeric so that it could be graphed on a continuous scale.

As far as unusual distributions, most of our data is either positively skewed or has a relatively normal distribution, suggesting that less is more for wine makers when it comes to any of these factors. Maybe they want to let the flavor of the grapes do the talking instead of making an extreme flavor in any direction.

The residual sugar of the wines is very low. We are dealing with a subset of very dry wines, which seems unusual. - -

Bivariate Plots Section

Variables to Quality Comparisons

Sulphates

It appears that sulphates in wine do not have a negative effect on quality as I expected, despite some peoples misgivings about the nature of sulphates in food and beverage. In fact, on this plot it appears that the more sulphates were in the wine the higher the rating the flavor of the wine got.

Total Sulfur Dioxide

Here we see that the total sulfur dioxide seems to have a weak negative relationship with quality. Indeed, our text file suggests that the more total sulfur dioxide there is, the more prominent their flavor can be, which must be unfavorable

Free Sulfur Dioxide

In the free sulfur dioxide and the total sulfur dioxide to quality graphs we see a very weak relationship. There is likely no relationship between free sulfur dioxide content and perceived quality of wine.

Fixed Acidity

Our fixed acidity appears to have a weak positive relationship with quality.

Volatile Acidity

More volatile acidity seems to decrease quality with a borderline weak/moderate relationship.

Citric Acid

The quality of wine seems to improve with citric acid with a weak relationship.

Residual Sugar

The residual sugar does not seem to have much of an effect on quality. This is likely due to the fact that most of the wines have a very similar amount of residual sugar.

Chlorides

There is a very weak negative correlation with salt/chlorides and quality.

Density

A similarly weak relationship exists between density and quality, with a minor skew toward lower density/more watery wines. Lower density wines should have a higher alcohol content and so it is hard to tell which of these variables cause the preference.

pH

There does not seem to be much of a relationship between quality and pH

Alcohol

The relationship between alcohol content and quality seems to be stronger than most of the data that we have looked at so far where the more alcohol the higher the quality of the wine. Alcohol leads to dryer flavors in wine and this looks more and more like this tasting was intended to find the best dry wine.

Residual Sugar to Alcohol

Now this graph is interesting because it does not seem to point to the expected conclusion that the amount of residual sugar would be roughly inversely proportionate to the amount of alcohol in the wine. Between 1.5 and 3 g/dm^3 of sugar the alcohol content varies from less than 8.5% to over 14% by volume. We can see in the outlier range there looks like there is a negative relationship with the alcohol content going down as the residual sugar goes up, but most of the data does not follow our expected trend. Our R value seems to indicate a very weak positive correlation between our variables. This is likely due to the very limited range of sugar in our wines giving us unlikely data.

Lets zoom in on to the bulk of the data area to see if we see any other trends

So our graph does not at all show the relationship we are expecting here.

Alcohol to Preservatives

Here, as should be expected, we see that the higher the alcohol content, the lower the preservatives in the wine. The relationship is weak across the board with volatile acidity and total sulfur dioxide having the strongest inverse relationships with alcohol.

Volatile Acidity to Citric Acid

There seems to be a moderate negative correlation with citric acid and volatile acidity. This goes against what I would have thought since citric acid is added after wine is made I would have expected that the volatile acidity would increase with the addition of citric acid.

Density to Alcohol

In this graph, as we would expect, the density of the wine goes down as the alcohol content goes up. Oddly, we would expect this because the alcohol is created by yeast eating sugar, so its strange with the uniform sugar content that this relationship is maintained.

Density to Residual Sugar

Though the relationship is a bit weaker, we can see that the relationship between density and sugar is maintained where the with should be more dense the more sugar it contains.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset? Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other
features (not the main feature(s) of interest)? What was the strongest
relationship you found?

The biggest predictors of wine quality by itself was mostly alcohol. Alcohol had a moderate relationship with wine quality with an r value of .48. Second to that was volatile acidity where it seems that the more volatile acidity there was the less liked was the wine. As explained in our text file, a lot of volatile acide leads to a vinegary taste in wine which many fine abhorrent so this data point makes sense. Citric acid seemed to be well liked with a coefficient of .23. I remember a manager touting that it added a springy, light taste to the wine that people enjoyed and it seems our experts agree to some extent. Our text file indicates something similar that the citric acid adds a freshness to wine.

There seemed to be no negative relationship with quality and sulphates in the alcohol, even perhaps, a weak positive correlation, though the more total sulfur dioxide there was the worse of a rating the wine got. The free sulfur dioxide seemed to make little difference in the wine quality.

Our sugar to alcohol relationship should have been inverse, but according to this data there is a very weak relationship. Despite this, the expected relationship of sugar to density and alcohol to density is as we expected with the higher sugar wines being more dense and the higher alcohol wines being less dense.

The strongest relationship was alcohol to density with a -.5 correlational coefficient indicating that there is a moderate relationship between those variables.

Our total sulfur dioxide, free sulfur dioxide, fixed acidity and volatile acidity to alcohol comparisons showed a weak negative relationship across the board giving some bit of credence to our hypotheses that the more alcohol a wine had, the less preservatives a wine make might add to it.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One: Residual Sugar

Description of Residual Sugar

This is a graph of the residual sugar in our wines in g/L (g/dm^3). This graph shows us that the bulk of our data falls within 1.5 to 2.5 g/dm^3. 1030 of our wines or over 64% of our 1599 observations fall in this range, which is an unusually low amount of sugar in wines.

Plot Two: Alcohol to Residual Sugar

Descriptionof Alcohol to Residual Sugar

In this graph we see the relationship between residual sugar in g/L and alcohol content by volume. We see by the R coefficient that there is a very weak correlation between the two when we should expect a strong correlation. This is likely due to our limited values of sugar where too many wines fall in a very tight limit on our sugar scale.

Plot Three: Alcohol and Residual Sugar with Density

Description of Alcohol and Residual Sugar with Density

This graph illustrates that despite the fact that our alochol and sugar ratios are not what we expect them to be, one relationship that we did expect remains. The red/orange area of the graph tends toward the top where it becomes more of a green/orange on the bottom. This indicates the lower density is toward the top where the alcohol content is higher and the higher density is toward the bottom where the residual sugar is higher.

Reflection

I believe this dataset to be incomplete or not representative of a good variety of wine due to the odd sugar content. Mostly I struggled with this concept as I initially felt I had done something wrong when I discovered this in our data. I was glad to find the explanation in the sugar content being so low. I was also pleased with the relationship between the preservatives and the alcohol where it seemed the relationship between alcohol and the various preservatives was vaguely negative which is what I expected.

It would be interesting to see finer relationships between quality and ratios of different substances, like the acid to sugar ratio and quality if the sugar was easier to work with and the same with chloride to sugar and acid.

It was interesting to see that sulphates were received more positively than most other aspects and that it is possible to taste the total sulfur dioxide and that its flavor made a noticeable impact on quality.
